Epizootic hem.disease, deer - USA (Missouri) 980926204622
[1
Date: Tue, 29 Sep 1998 22:20:36 -0400
From: "Angela M. Lee" <finchley@flash.net>
ProMED-mail Special Correspondent
Source: news media 29 Sep 1998, edited
[Posting delayed in vain hope of getting virology results - Mod.JW

Reports of deer killed by EHD virus have increased in northern Missouri, and
veterinarians have found that some cattle in the region are showing similar
symptoms that might be attributed to epizootic hemorrhagic disease.
"It's widespread across northern Missouri," state veterinarian John Hunt
said. "I've talked to vets in Mexico, Monroe City, Kirksville, Palmyra,
Trenton -- the northern tiers of counties. One veterinarian called me and
said she had seen a handful of these cases in eight or 10 years of practice
but has seen more than that in the last few weeks."
Veterinarians at Missouri University's large animal clinic have examined
five cows that had those symptoms and tested positive either for the
hemorrhagic disease or a genetically similar infection known as bluetongue
virus. Two of the infected cows were from around Kirksville, two were from
near Moberly and the fifth was from a farm about 30 miles north of Columbia.
"We don't see the severity of the disease that you would in deer," said Jeff
Lakritz, associate professor of veterinary science. Still, "several vets
have told me that some cows were looking pretty sick, and it looked like
they were going to have to put them down."
Dead deer attributed to the virus have been reported in 17 Missouri
counties, up from 12 counties two weeks ago. Lonnie Hansen, a wildlife
biologist with the state
Department of Conservation, said the increase was "probably due to better
reporting."
In recent weeks, deer have been reported dead or dying from the virus in
Boone, Cole, Callaway, Howard, Randolph, Mercer, Grundy, Daviess, Adair,
Macon, Chariton, Putnam, Linn, Jackson, Miller, Camden and Carter counties.
Ten years ago, the virus wiped out an estimated 10,000 deer in Missouri --
up to 20 percent of the wild herd in some counties. That outbreak was
concentrated in the southeast quadrant of the state.
"When you have an outbreak of EHD in deer, it is not uncommon for cows to be
affected," said David Stallknecht, a University of Georgia wildlife
epidemiologist who is working with Missouri officials to study the deer
fatalities. Stallknecht said such outbreaks have occurred "pretty much
throughout the Southeast," though cattle in southeastern states apparently
have developed an immunity. Outbreaks in deer and cows have coincided in
West Virginia in 1993 and Indiana in 1996, Stallknecht said. "Where this has
affected cows is on the northern range of this virus in the U.S." Tests have
shown that about one-third of infected deer die, one-third develop nonfatal
symptoms and one-third show no symptoms, said Stallknecht.
The Missouri conservation agency said that symptoms in deer include
weakness, open sores or swelling of the mouth and tongue and bleeding from
mouth, nose, eyes or rectum. Infected cattle show excessive salivation,
weakness, stiffness or lameness
or sores on the tongue, mouth and hooves, Hunt said. Infected cattle can be
treated with antibiotics and an analgesic, Lakritz said.
---
[Until the virology is done there is no knowing whether this is EHDv in
cattle or merely a coincident series of outbreaks of bovine bluetongue/blue
tongue (Charlie insists on the former, I was brought up on the latter). We
have had a number of similar reports as this from individuals in Missouri,
which I had passed to folk at MU veterinary college for comment but have
received no replies, informed or otherwise. If anyone does have any hard
data on the cause(s) of the bovine illness, it would be appreciated if they
would share it with us. If any of you can grab Dave Stallknecht (with my
best wishes) and get him to comment, that would also be appreciated -
