Date: Tue, 6 Oct 1998 18:51:31 -0400
From: "Angela M. Lee" <finchley@flash.net>
ProMED-mail Special Correspondent
Source: Tribune Online News Story
http://showmenews.com/news/1998100601.html
http://showmenews.com/news/index.html
http://showmenews.com/archive
October 6, 1998
Mortality rising from virus in deer
Whitetail deaths spread to 25 counties in Missouri
-------------------------------------------------------------
By George Mazurak of the Tribune's staff [edited, MHJ
Deaths of virus-infected deer have spread to 25 Missouri counties, and
mortality in some places could rival losses 10 years ago, when an estimated
10 000 wild deer in the state died. "In some counties, it seems every bit as
bad as it was" in 1988, "if not more so," said biologist Lonnie Hansen of
the Missouri Department of Conservation.
Epizootic hemorrhagic disease virus exists naturally in wild deer but
periodically has resulted in fatal outbreaks in Missouri and other states.
Those EHD outbreaks have coincided with the outbreak of similar, though
mostly nonfatal, illnesses in cattle. This year's EHD outbreak in deer has
spurred the state conservation agency to begin a 10-year study to learn how
widespread EHD occurs in wild deer and why some deer don't develop symptoms
from the virus but others do.
Next month, during the 11-day firearms season for deer, conservation agents
plan to draw 1000 to 1500 blood samples from carcasses brought by hunters
to check-in stations, Hansen said. Agents will take a smaller number of
samples from deer carcasses in years when there is no significant outbreak
of EHD. Hansen said that EHD seems to be having the most severe impact in
Daviess, Grundy, Putnam, Linn, Macon and Adair counties in North-central
Missouri. Other deer infected with EHD have been reported in Boone, Audrain,
Callaway, Howard, Andrew, DeKalb, Harrison, Livingston, Mercer, Sullivan,
Chariton, Randolph, Schuyler, Scotland, Cole, Jackson, Crawford and on the
border of Pike and Ralls counties. All but three of the counties are north
of the Missouri River.
Researchers are studying the relationship between EHD in deer and symptoms
of bluetongue virus or EHD in cattle. Tests at the MU Veterinary Medical
Diagnostic Lab have been inconclusive regarding the origin of EHD in cattle
or whether bluetongue virus in cattle might somehow have been affected by
EHD in deer. The lab conducted virology tests on 10 cows from eight counties
and found the virus in two cows, one each from Monroe and Harrison counties.
The MU lab found that serology tests [which don't always separate clearly
between BT & EHD antibodies were positive for EHD in 17 of 25 cows,
including the two cows that had EHD-positive virology tests. Efforts are
under way to grow the virus in some of the 17 cases to determine whether
they had been exposed to EHD or bluetongue, said veterinary science
associate professor Peg Miller. But the process takes a couple of weeks and
is not always successful.
